{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BSw9jRAVpRBvF2mYkeaZ8y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logic in the handler looks exactly the same as in `prompt.go`. Let me think about this differently.\n\nThe bug report says \"clicking on a step shows the filename but doesn't load contents.\" Let me look at the frontend code more carefully.\n\nIn the `openDrawer` function:\n1. It shows step metadata including `step.config.prompt` which displays `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` - this is the \"filename\" the user sees\n2. It fetches from the content API endpoint\n\nThe content API endpoint handler tries to read the file. If it succeeds, it returns the content. If it fails, it falls through.\n\n\nThe workflow API passes the raw config values directly to the frontend, so `step.config.prompt` contains the literal `file(\"...\")` string. When the frontend tries to fetch the content, the backend should parse and resolve that file path â€” but something's failing in that resolution.\n\nLooking at the fetch logic, I'm checking if there's a JavaScript issue with how the response is being handled or displayed.\n\nActually, I think I see the problem â€” when the response isn't okay, it returns an empty string, but when it is okay, it returns `r.text()` which is a Promise. Both work fine in the chain since non-Promise values get wrapped automatically, so that's not it.\n\nLet me consider whether this could be a CORS or routing issue instead.\n\nLooking at the Go 1.22 ServeMux patterns, `{workflow}` should only match a single path segment, so the route `/api/projects/{name}/workflows/{workflow}/steps/{step}/content` should correctly parse the project label, workflow name, and step name without any path consumption issues.\n\nI'm wondering if the real issue is simpler â€” maybe the config display is showing the raw `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` syntax string, and the user expects to see the actual file contents instead. The content loaded in the drawer below might be working fine, but the metadata section above is just displaying the filename reference rather than resolving it.\n\nActually, looking back at the error description more carefully, it says the file contents aren't being loaded and displayed at all. Let me trace through the handler logic to see where the file fetch might be failing.\n\nExamining the handler...\n\nI see the issue now. The handler is checking if the prompt value starts with `file(\"` and ends with `\")`, then extracting the path and reading the file. But there's a logic problem hereâ€”if the file read fails with an error, the code doesn't write anything back to the response, it just falls through. And then it checks for a `run` command, but if neither the prompt nor the run command exist, it returns a 404. The real problem might be that `step.Config` doesn't have the keys we expect, or the file path extraction is off. Looking at the handler logic, it correctly identifies `file(\"` prefixes for prompt values and plain strings for run values. But examining the develop.cloche file more carefully â€” the `run` key stores the command without quotes, while `prompt` stores the full `file(\"...\")` expression. I'm wondering if there's a mismatch in how the config map keys are being referenced.\n\nLet me trace through the parseStep function to see exactly what keys get stored in the step configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1926,"cache_read_input_tokens":44806,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1926},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a37f3516-6a98-45b4-b440-44c340a4d486","uuid":"c8dcee20-6e48-42a0-a7f1-cc53a26c80ea"}
