ripts/test.sh\")`, it would return the string `file(\"scripts/test.sh\")` instead of the file contents!\n\nAH HA! That might be the bug! The handler only handles `file(\"...\")` syntax for `prompt` config values but not for `run` config values!\n\nBut wait, looking at the parser test, the `run` value for script steps is stored as a plain string (the command). Does the DSL support `file(\"...\")` for `run` values?\n\nLooking at the parser, `parseValue()` handles `file(\"...\")` for ANY value, so `run = file(\"scripts/test.sh\")` would store that literal string in `Config[\"run\"]`. But the handler only processes `file(\"...\")` for `prompt` values, not `run` values. Let me check if any actual workflows use `file(\"...\")` for `run` â€” looking at develop.cloche, it's just plain command strings like `run = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"`, not file references. So the handler would return the command string directly, which seems right for that case.\n\nThe issue description mentions \"script file\" not loading its contents properly. Maybe the problem is that when a step has a `file(\"...\")` reference for `run`, the drawer shows the reference but the content area doesn't load the actual file contents. Let me write a test to verify this behavior.\n\nActually, waitâ€”I just spotted something in the JavaScript. The `openDrawer` function finds the step from the workflow's steps array, then iterates through `step.config` to display metadata. But I need to see how the content loading works...\n\nExamining the drawer code more carefully... I'm realizing the Go template is outputting the raw value without quotes, so `projectLabel` would be assigned to a JavaScript variable reference rather than a string literal â€” which means it would be undefined unless that variable exists in the page context. The `html/template` package should handle escaping in script blocks, but I need to verify how it actually renders this value. I'm verifying how Go's `html/template` handles string encoding in 