{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UfnW3xGc1p9DFH65ZyD6q2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the issue! Looking at the diff, the ORIGINAL code had:\n\n```go\nif prompt := step.Config[\"prompt\"]; prompt != \"\" {\n    data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, prompt))\n    if err == nil {\n        w.Write(data)\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe original code tried to read the file using the ENTIRE prompt value as a path, including the `file(\"...\")` wrapper. So it would try to read a file named `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` which doesn't exist.\n\nThe CURRENT code (with the diff applied) fixes this by handling the `file(\"...\")` syntax:```go\n\n\nif strings.HasPrefix(prompt, `file(\"`) && strings.HasSuffix(prompt, `\")`) {\n    path := prompt[6 : len(prompt)-2]\n    data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, path))\n```\n\nParsing the file reference syntax...\n\nThe git diff shows the working tree has the fix that strips the `file(\"...\")` wrapper and extracts the actual path, while the committed HEAD version just passes the raw prompt string directly to `os.ReadFile`, which fails because it's trying to open a file literally named `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` instead of the intended path. The fix extracts the actual file path from the `file(\"...\")` wrapper syntax that the DSL parser generates, then reads the file from that extracted path instead of trying to use the wrapper string directly. The old code also used different config key names like `command` instead of what's being used now. So the real issue is twofold â€” the prompt handler doesn't strip the `file(\"...\")` wrapper to get the actual path, and the script handler is checking the wrong config keys. The fix addresses both by stripping that wrapper and using the correct `run` key instead. Looking at the git status, these changes are already staged in the working tree but haven't been committed yet.\n\nNow I need to verify whether the fix is complete and correct, or if there's more work needed. The fix handles the three main casesâ€”reading files with the `file(\"...\")` syntax, returning plain string prompts, and handling run commandsâ€”but there's a gap where a missing file silently falls through without returning anything, which should probably return a 404 or the original string instead.\n\nLooking at the actual behavior though, if the file doesn't exist, the code eventually hits the 404 handler anyway since `run` would be empty for agent steps, so it's not breaking anythingâ€”just potentially confusing for users who see \"No content available\" when a file is missing. That's more of a UX improvement than a critical bug.\n\nI should also check the template changes to see if there are frontend modifications needed alongside this handler fix.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":732,"cache_read_input_tokens":72713,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":732},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a37f3516-6a98-45b4-b440-44c340a4d486","uuid":"b42d9698-cd91-4243-958b-c70cbc39bd5e"}
